   <titles>
      <title>Cramer’s Rule</title>
      <plain.title>Cramer’s Rule</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Consider a system of <math>
                     <latex>n</latex>
                  </math> linear equations in <math>
                     <latex>n</latex>
                  </math> unknowns whose coefficient matrix is invertible. We know then that this system of linear has exactly one solution. Here we use determinants to build a formula which computes this unique solution.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="CramerRule_Thm.xml"/>
            <para>
               <para.body>A nice application of Cramer’s rule is the following theorem. It provides a formula for computing the inverse of an invertible matrix.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="MatrixInverseFormula_Thm.xml"/>
            <para>
               <para.body>A special case of the formula for the inverse of a matrix is the following simple formula for the inverse of an invertible <math>
                     <latex>(2,2)</latex>
                  </math>-matrix.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="MatrixInverseFormula22_Thm.xml"/>
         </block.body>
      </block>
